<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1923-12-28T02:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1923-12-28T02:00:00-05:00" n="455" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d455">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">493.11/947: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Schurman</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1923-12-28T15:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">December 28,
                                        1923—3 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received December 28—8:02
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>426. My despatch no. 1905, November 5. Lengthy identical note dated
                            December 26 just received from Chinese Foreign Office refuses to accept
                            the views expressed in the joint notes of February 24th and November 5th
                                [<hi rend="italic">3d</hi>] on the principal ground that the
                            provision of law [<hi rend="italic">protocol?</hi>] fixes gold
                            equivalent of the indemnity in the respective currencies now [<hi rend="italic">not?</hi>] in gold specie. Many other arguments
                            advanced. Chinese Foreign Office will publish the note today. It will be
                            discussed by the Ministers concerned. Copy by mail.<note n="23" xml:id="d455fn23"><hi rend="italic">Post</hi>, <ref target="#pg_600">p. 600</ref>.</note></p>
                        <closer>For the Minister:<lb/><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Bell</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>